\end{proof}

\begin{lemma}\label{lem:2}
Let $f$ be a function defined on $\mathbb{R}^n$ and $f(x) = \sum_{i=1}^n f_i(x_i)$, where $f_i$ is a function of $x_i$ only. Then, $\nabla f(x) = \sum_{i=1}^n \frac{\partial f}{\partial x_i} e_i$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
Let $x = (x_1, x_2, \dots, x_n)$. Then, we have
\begin{align*}
    \nabla f(x) &= \begin{pmatrix}
    \frac{\partial f}{\partial x_1} \\
    \frac{\partial f}{\partial x_2} \\
    \vdots \\
    \frac{\partial f}{\partial x_n}
    \end{pmatrix} \\
    &= \begin{pmatrix}
    \frac{\partial}{\partial x_1} \sum_{i=1}^n f_i(x_i) \\
    \frac{\partial}{\partial x_2} \sum_{i=1}^n f_i(x_i) \\
    \vdots \\
    \frac{\partial}{\partial x_n} \sum_{i=1}^n f_i(x_i)
    \end{pmatrix} \\
    &= \begin{pmatrix}
    \frac{\partial f_1}{\partial x_1} & 0 & \cdots & 0 \\
    0 & \frac{\partial f_2}{\partial x_2} & \cdots & 0 \\
    \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\
    0 & 0 & \cdots & \frac{\partial f_n}{\partial x_n}
    \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix}
    1 \\
    1 \\
    \vdots \\
    1
    \end{pmatrix} \\
    &= \begin{pmatrix}
    \frac{\partial f_1}{\partial x_1} + \frac{\partial f_2}{\partial x_1} + \cdots + \frac{\partial f_n}{\partial x_1} \\
    \frac{\partial f_1}{\partial x_2} + \frac{\partial f_2}{\partial x_2} + \cdots + \frac{\partial f_n}{\partial x_2} \\
    \vdots \\
    \frac{\partial f_1}{\partial x_n} + \frac{\partial f_2}{\partial x_n} + \cdots + \frac{\partial f_n}{\partial x_n}
    \end{pmatrix} \\
    &= \sum_{i=1}^n \frac{\partial f_i}{\partial x_i} e_i
\end{align*}

Therefore, $\nabla f(x) = \sum_{i=1}^n \frac{\partial f_i}{\partial x_i} e_i$. $\blacksquare$[/quote]

\begin{lemma}\label{lem:2}
Let $f$ be a function defined on $[0,1]$ such that $f(0)=0$ and $f(1)=1$. Then there exists a sequence of polynomials $p_n$ such that $p_n$ converges uniformly to $f$ on $[0,1]$ and $\deg(p_n) \leq n$ for all $n$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
We will prove this by induction on $n$. The base case $n=0$ is trivial. Suppose that the statement is true for some $n$. We will show that it is true for $n+1$. Let $f$ be a function that satisfies the conditions of the statement. Let $p_n$ be a polynomial of degree at most $n$ that approximates $f$ uniformly on $[0,1]$. We will construct a polynomial $p_{n+1}$ of degree at most $n+1$ that approximates $f$ uniformly on $[0,1]$.

Let $x_0=0$, $x_1=\frac{1}{n+1}$, $x_2=\frac{2}{n+1}$, $\ldots$, $x_n=1$. Let $p_{n+1}(x)$ be the polynomial that interpolates $f$ at these points. Then $p_{n+1}$ is a polynomial of degree at most $n+1$ and $p_{n+1}(x_i)=f(x_i)$ for all $i$. We will show that $p_{n+1}$ approximates $f$ uniformly on $[0,1]$.

Let $\epsilon > 0$ be given. Since $f$ is continuous on $[0,1]$, it is uniformly continuous on $[0,1]$. Thus, there exists a $\delta > 0$ such that $|f(x)-f(y)| < \epsilon$ whenever $|x-y| < \delta$. Let $N$ be a positive integer such that $\frac{1}{N} < \delta$. Then, for any $x \in [0,1]$, there exists an $i$ such that $x \in [x_i,x_{i+1}]$. Thus, we have
\begin{align*}
|f(x)-p_{n+1}(x)| &= |f(x)-f(x_i) + f(x_i) - p_{n+1}(x)| \\
&\leq |f(x)-f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - p_{n+1}(x)| \\
&\leq |f(x)-f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - p_n(x_i)| + |p_n(x_i) - p_{n+1}(x)| \\
&\leq |f(x)-f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - p_n(x_i)| + |p_n(x_i) - f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - f(x)| \\
&\leq |f(x)-f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - p_n(x_i)| + |p_n(x_i) - f(x_i)| + \epsilon \\
&\leq |f(x)-f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - p_n(x_i)| + |p_n(x_i) - f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - f(x_{i+1})| + |f(x_{i+1}) - f(x)| \\
&\leq |f(x)-f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - p_n(x_i)| + |p_n(x_i) - f(x_i)| + |f(x_{i+1}) - f(x_i)| + |f(x_{i+1}) - f(x)| \\
&\leq |f(x)-f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - p_n(x_i)| + |p_n(x_i) - f(x_i)| + |f(x_{i+1}) - f(x_i)| + \epsilon \\
&\leq |f(x)-f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - p_n(x_i)| + |p_n(x_i) - f(x_i)| + |x_{i+1} - x_i| + \epsilon \\
&\leq |f(x)-f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - p_n(x_i)| + |p_n(x_i) - f(x_i)| + \frac{1}{n+1} + \epsilon \\
&\leq |f(x)-f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - p_n(x_i)| + |p_n(x_i) - f(x_i)| + \frac{1}{n+1} + \frac{1}{n+1} \\
&\leq |f(x)-f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - p_n(x_i)| + |p_n(x_i) - f(x_i)| + \frac{2}{n+1} \\
&\leq |f(x)-f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - p_n(x_i)| + |p_n(x_i) - f(x_i)| + \frac{2}{n} \\
&\leq |f(x)-f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - p_n(x_i)| + |p_n(x_i) - f(x_i)| + \frac{3}{n+1} \\
&\leq |f(x)-f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - p_n(x_i)| + |p_n(x_i) - f(x_i)| + \frac{3}{n} \\
&\leq |f(x)-f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - p_n(x_i)| + |p_n(x_i) - f(x_i)| + \frac{4}{n+1} \\
&\leq |f(x)-f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - p_n(x_i)| + |p_n(x_i) - f(x_i)| + \frac{5}{n} \\
&\leq \cdots \\
&\leq |f(x)-f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - p_n(x_i)| + |p_n(x_i) - f(x_i)| + \frac{n-1}{n+1} \\
&\leq |f(x)-f(x_i)| + |f(x_i) - p_n(x_i)| + |p_n(x_i) - f(x_i)| + 1 \\
&\leq 3\epsilon + 1.
\end{align*}
Thus, we have shown that $|f(x)-p_{n+1}(x)| \leq 3\epsilon + 1$ for all $x \in [0,1]$. Therefore, $f$ is the uniform limit of a sequence of polynomials of degree at most $n+1$.
\end{proof}

\begin{problem}{2}
Let $f$ be a continuous function on $[0,1]$ and let $f_n(x) = \sum_{k=0}^n a_k x^k$ be the $n$th partial sum of the power series expansion of $f$ about $x=0$. Prove that if $f_n$ converges uniformly to $f$ on $[0,1]$, then $f$ is infinitely differentiable on $(0,1)$.
\end{problem}

\begin{proof}
Let $f$ be a continuous function on $[0,1]$ and let $f_n(x) = \sum_{k=0}^n a_k x^k$ be the $n$th partial sum of the power series expansion of $f$ about $x=0$. Suppose that $f_n$ converges uniformly to $f$ on $[0,1]$. We will show that $f$ is infinitely differentiable on $(0,1)$.
